    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "That's an interesting distinction. You mentioned that Case B might lead to harsher sentencing if the judge sees those factors as contributing to criminal behavior. Can you expand on that? Specifically, why would a \"sporadic employment history\" or living in an \"underserved urban area\" be viewed as factors that increase the likelihood of recidivism or justify a more punitive approach, rather than being seen as mitigating factors like poverty or lack of opportunity?",
