      "content": "Some judges might view those background factors not as excuses, but as evidence of a lack of personal responsibility or poor decision-making, suggesting the defendant is more likely to reoffend. They might interpret instability as a failure to utilize available resources or make better choices, which can lead to a more punitive stance. In some judicial mindsets, these socioeconomic issues are seen as character flaws rather than external barriers, thus justifying a stronger deterrent sentence.",
      "source": "target",
